3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates APT/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using a time-weighted average of the premium index. The funding rate is determined by the difference between perpetual and spot prices, with payments occurring between long and short position holders. MEXC's zero maker fee structure allows arbitrageurs to enter and exit positions without additional trading costs beyond the 0.03% taker fee."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","APT","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"APT represents Aptos, a Layer 1 blockchain that often experiences significant price volatility during network updates and ecosystem developments. This volatility creates frequent funding rate imbalances as traders position for price movements, generating arbitrage opportunities for sophisticated traders on MEXC's platform."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"APT/USDT funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.1% to 0.3% per 8-hour period, with extreme rates reaching ±0.5% during major Aptos ecosystem announcements. The pair shows strong correlation with broader Layer 1 sentiment, often spiking positive during DeFi growth phases and turning negative during market corrections. Historical data indicates funding rates tend to normalize within 24-48 hours after initial volatility spikes, creating predictable arbitrage windows."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create significant advantages for APT/USDT funding arbitrage compared to traditional exchanges charging 0.02-0.05% maker fees. Cross-exchange arbitrage becomes profitable when funding rate differentials exceed 0.05% after accounting for transfer costs and slippage. The 8-hour funding interval provides multiple daily opportunities, with most profitable positions occurring during Asia-Pacific trading hours when APT volume peaks."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"APT's mid-tier volume on MEXC can result in wider spreads during volatile periods, increasing execution risk for large arbitrage positions. Order book depth typically ranges from $50-200k within 1% of mid-price, requiring position sizing considerations for institutional traders. Regulatory uncertainty around MEXC and potential delisting risks should factor into long-term arbitrage strategies, particularly for positions held across multiple funding periods."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does MEXC calculate APT/USDT funding rates?","answer":"MEXC calculates APT/USDT funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. Funding payments are automatically exchanged between long and short position holders at these intervals based on the calculated rate."},{"question":"What are typical APT funding rates on MEXC?","answer":"APT/USDT funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.1% to 0.3% per 8-hour period under normal market conditions. During high volatility or major Aptos ecosystem events, rates can spike to ±0.5% before normalizing within 24-48 hours."},{"question":"How do MEXC's zero maker fees affect APT arbitrage?","answer":"Zero maker fees significantly reduce the cost basis for funding rate arbitrage strategies on APT/USDT. This creates a competitive advantage over exchanges charging maker fees, making smaller funding rate differentials profitable for arbitrageurs."},{"question":"What's the minimum funding rate threshold for profitable APT arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"With zero maker fees, APT arbitrage on MEXC becomes profitable at funding rates above 0.05-0.08% per period, accounting for the 0.03% taker fee and minimal spread costs. Cross-exchange strategies may require higher thresholds depending on transfer and execution costs."}]}]
